[27.084005, "o", "cat finding.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[27.084965, "o", "FINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocked by Improper String Matching Rules\r\n\r\nBLOCKING RULES:\r\n- Line: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Line: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Followed by DROP rules for ports 80 and 443\r\n\r\nROOT CAUSE:\r\nThe iptables ruleset implements string matching that only accepts HTTP/HTTPS traffic containing the string \"Mozilla\" in the packet payload. This appears to be an attempt at user-agent filtering, possibly for blocking bots or implementing basic access control.\r\n\r\nWHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP DOESN'T:\r\n- SSH (port 22): Has a simple unconditional ACCEPT rule with no string matching requirements\r\n- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Require the string \"Mozilla\" to be present in the packet data\r\n- When curl connects without a custom User-Agent, it sends \"curl/X.X.X\" which doesn't contain \"Mozilla\"\r\n- The traffic fails the string match, bypasses the ACCEPT rule, and hits the subsequent DROP rules\r\n\r\nWHY THIS APP"]
[27.085048, "o", "ROACH IS PROBLEMATIC:\r\n1. String matching on packet payloads is unreliable - it may not catch the User-Agent in fragmented packets or encrypted traffic (HTTPS)\r\n2. Legitimate tools, scripts, and API clients often don't use Mozilla-based User-Agents\r\n3. Attackers can trivially bypass this by adding \"Mozilla\" to their requests\r\n4. This is not effective for rate limiting or geo-blocking (which require connection tracking or GeoIP modules)\r\n5. For HTTPS (port 443), this rule is essentially useless since the User-Agent is encrypted in TLS traffic\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDATION:\r\nIf the goal is rate limiting, use the 'recent' or 'limit' iptables modules. If the goal is geo-blocking, use the 'geoip' module with MaxMind databases. If the goal is bot filtering, implement this at the application/web server level (nginx, apache) where you can properly parse HTTP headers, not at the firewall level.\r\n"]
[27.085122, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
